				<b><a href="javascript:openWindow(9,1913);"><font face="Verdana" size="1" >9</font></a></b>
				<b><a href="javascript:openWindow(10,1913);"><font face="Verdana" size="1" >10</font></a></b>
				<font face="Verdana" size="1"><b>best</b></font>
			</td>
		</td>
		
	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				  The magician is basically a wizard who exchanges some spell firepower for pets and exchanges the wizard's teleporting for the ability to conjure items.  It's hard to tell who came out ahead in the deal.<BR>
   Handy as conjuring items is, you will have little luck selling the stuff that you conjure.  On the other hand at least you have free bandages, food, and water at any time as well as the ability to conjure up a (better quality than the normal ones sold) dagger when needed.  Later you can summon items other classes find very handy indeed, like armor and arrows.  (Conjured bags are nice too, just be sure to make sure everything is cleared out of them before camping or you'll lose them.  Note: Items placed into conjured bags weigh NOTHING.).  The downside of conjuring, and the reason why you will have a hard time selling many of the things you conjure, is that as the possessor of a summon item camps all of the conjured items they are holding are null and void.<BR>
    As mentioned before, when it comes to firepower compared to a wizard, the magician pretty much swapped some of the wizard's firepower in exchange for the ability to use pets who can inflict and take damage.  Magician pets are generally alot more durable than the Enchanter's animated daggers and can take orders (/pet attack, /pet as you were, /pet follow, /pet guard me, and /pet guard here).  Only the necromancer has compariably durable pets.  Pets will stay with your magician until you zone or until one of you dies.  Unlike necromancers, magician pets cannot use weapons, although they often have abilities of their own (explained later).<BR>
   You can only have one pet at a time and each attempt at conjuring a pet costs a malachite reagent in addition to mana.  Malachite reagents are available at most Mage Guilds in most cities, usually found on either a shopkeeper inside (as is the case in the Gnome and Human cities) or in a store just outside of the mage guild (as is the case for the High Elven city).  You may have to search around a bit to find it.<BR>
   Pets are upgradable each 4 levels (with your first magician pets spells being scribable at level 4).  At these intervals there's pet conjuring spells for the four popular elements: Earth, Water, Air and Fire.  Generally each elemental type has cirtain unique capabilities...<BR>
   Earth elementals tend to be one of the more durable types and inflict fair damage.  They move relatively slow.  Earth elementals do about 5-10 points of damage per attack per spell rank.<BR>
   Fire elementals are not as durable as Earth or Water elementals, but occationally cast Radiate on themselves so that monsters attacking them hurt themselves in the process.  Contrary to popular belief, Fire Elementals appear not to do very much damage in their attacks, about 5 pts per spell rank.<BR>
   Water Elementals seem to be relatively durable and hit relatively hard.  They seem to consistantly influct 10 pts per attack per spell level (less random than Earth), and endure about as much damage, perhaps a little less or more.  <BR>
   Air Elementals are about as durable as fire elementals but do not cast radiate, instead they cast invisibility on themselves.  This of course allows you to sneak around with your own invisiblity spell without your elemental attracting unwanted attention.  They seem to inflict simular damage than fire elementals, about 5 points of damage per spell rank.<BR>
   It should be noted that when you use a elemental conjuring spell, it summons an elemental whose level equals the level of the conjuring spell with about a 1 level variance.  This means if you conure an elemental with your level 4 spell it will conjure an elemental whose level is between 3 and 5.   The unfortunate consiquence of this is while you will be able to easily handle equal leveled monsters on the levels in which you first recieve your summoning spells, once you reach the level right before you get the next rank of summoning spells you will find your elemental dreadfully underpowered for the task.<BR>
   Some play Tips:<BR>
   If your elemental seems near death (as will happen alot at lower levels), it can be beneficial to move up and have the monster attack you instead as that way your elemental will still be alive and inflicting damage.<BR>
   If it seems during combat like your going to die when your elemental dies, in most cases if you have been paying attention you should have time to cast your gate spell and get out of there before the monster finishes off your elemental.<BR>
   Elementals refuse to attack monsters that are too high leveled for them, leaving you to die.  If your elemental just wanders around randomly screaming threats when you tell it to attack then chances are that monster is too powerful and if you plan to fight it expect to do so alone.<BR>
    While having a variety of elementals can be handy for different situations, you can save much needed money by focusing on just one until such time as you feel you have enough to spare to pick up the others.  Earth and Water elementals are generally the good damage sponges, with Fire being handy for having the monster take damage as he takes it down and Air being handy for stealth.<BR>
<BR>
   Note: This only covers up until level 8.  From here on in your elemental durability tends to even out a bit as  this point (I.e. your level 8 elemental can last longer against a level 12 monster than a level 4 elemental would last against a level 8 monster).  Even so, it increasingly becomes an important issue to have your magician do the damage via spells while your elemental is alive.  While Magicians are good soloers initially, many higher level Magicians feel much safer in a group, which is why I wonder who got the better end of the deal - Magicians with their lesser damage spells but elementals or Wizards with their full strength damage spells?
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
